text: First this is a straight Crimson Tide knock off ... a great movie for it's time and cheap imitation of our time is what we have here. Second why does it have to be RUSSIANS ... I get they're the big baddie used as the forever heel in Hollywood but as far as geopolitical submarine conflict that is more realistic ... use North Korea and I'll explain why. North Korea has non-nuclear subs so blowing nuclear waste into the Ocean can be neglected, second if it's a conflict with North Korea it wouldn't cascade into thermo-nuclear winter ... an unnecessary plot point since if it is a WW3 level conflict with Russia I tend to ask where are the Brits, the French, the Chinese, the Indians because this may be American centric POV but WW3 is very global and movies that overlook the geopolitics like NATO or buffer conflicts on land as Presidents get kidnapped/ rescued/ re-installed/ etc is just a whole lot of variables left on the cutting room floor. I say this because I'm Canadian and I just saw a sub being blown up in the Arvtic North I presume ... wtf who's cleaning up that environmental mess? This is why North Korea makes more sense since they pose a large regional threat but would be confined to that region for now ... heck you can show a bunch of NATO bureaucrats debating why they should not engage ... that just adds a better plot point and tension to feed that American unilateralism approach; it's more realistic then this mess of a plot.

text: Despite the obvious negative reviews of the film, I decided to watch it, just for the giggles. It was by no means a smart film... but to my surprise, it was a fun film. I mean sure, a situation like that would never have happened, and I am not even talking about US submarine rescuing a Russian president fro a coup attempt. I am talking about a coup itself - westerners have a strange and somewhat comic picture of what Russia is and how it works. But that aside, it was actually a fun action packed film - as long as you don't project real life politics into it.  And why would you - it is a film of a made up scenario.  The one thing that spoiled the fun and the narrative presented is near the very end. SPOILER INCOMING!  When the crew of the Russian destroyer fires at the coup command center. At one point, they protect the US submarine because their former commander and mentor, as well as president, is on board that sub. That is fine. But then, as a response, they fire into a base where hundreds if not thousands of their friends are stationed, just following orders, probably not knowing what is going on.  They could have fired at those surface to sea missile battery or something similar, prevent the damage to US sub while doing minimum damage to their countrymen and alerting the entire Russian military.  But no, they fired at their own base with thousands of their countrymen.  Apart from that, the storytelling was, if not realistic, at least logical to some extent. Or better said, it followed one logic, no matter how ridiculous it was. But then, at an instant, the logic that you've built upon, is broken. So even if you decided to enjoy a rather funny action flick, the film kicks you in the nuts with one scene at the end. Instead of it, they could have had a scene where the destroyer alerts the fleet and the army and Russian choppers with Spetsnaz start landing and arresting the defense minister, killing the minister's lap dog (commander of his personal guard) in the process.  It would have been a better ending, in accord with logic whey worked with through the entire film.  So even if I come from the anti-American surroundings, I actually had fun watching it. Just shut off your brain and enjoy an action flick. As you would with Rambo or some sci-fi film. It's a made up story, don't get real world politics into it. If you can't take off political glasses off, then skip the film. I mean I watched it as I would Iron Sky - a crazy over the top story with some action. So it was fun. If you go into it wanting a realism of a historic documentary, fine, just watch it and bitch about it alone, don't spoil the fun for others.

text: Title: Hunter Killer A U.S. submarine, the USS Tampa Bay, vanishes while shadowing a Russian Akula-class submarine in the Arctic. Rear Admiral John Fisk sends a Virginia-class submarine, the USS Arkansas, under the command of newly-promoted and unorthodox Commander Joe Glass to investigate. At the same time, a Navy SEAL team under the command of Lieutenant Bill Beaman is sent in to discreetly observe a Russian naval base, but their mission is swiftly complicated when Martinelli, the team's new DM recruit, is rendered unconscious during the HALO drop. When they arrive at the naval base, they witness defense minister Dmitri Durov conducting a coup d'eta and taking Russian President Zakarin prisoner, and swiftly realize that Durov intends to trigger a war.
